00:05:44.949 --> 00:05:47.240
It's tough trying to research
everything and figure out

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:50.090
when did the accordion start and
when did it get into the phase

00:05:50.090 --> 00:05:52.229
that it is in now?

00:05:52.229 --> 00:05:54.270
And there are many different
kinds of accordions,

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:55.340
which I'll also say.

00:05:55.340 --> 00:05:58.880
So around the 1820s,
1830s, accordion

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:02.240
began as just something
to have an organ

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:04.250
that you'd be able to
almost put in your pocket

00:06:04.250 --> 00:06:05.780
and walk around with.

00:06:05.780 --> 00:06:08.510
And the idea was to have
these little reeds that you

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:10.790
would play and blow into.

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:12.740
Organetto was kind
of the first one.

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:15.560
And then they started
to look kind of like,

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:17.960
if anybody knows a
bandoneon or concertina

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:21.440
they play in Argentina, they
started to look more like that.

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:24.930
And then around 1900,
people started saying,

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:27.570
why don't we put a
piano on the right side?

00:06:27.570 --> 00:06:31.520
And so the actual term of this
instrument that I'm playing

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:33.590
is called the piano accordion.

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:37.372
And that has mainly become
popular in the United States.

00:06:37.372 --> 00:06:39.830
And it's kind of interesting
how every single country plays

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:43.160
a different accordion, and I'll
draw different ones that we do.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.340
So the guy that made the
accordion popular in the United

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:48.800
States was a person
named Guido Deiro.

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:53.417
And he came to the United
States in 1908, brought

00:06:53.417 --> 00:06:54.500
the first piano accordion.

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:56.540
And that was in
the vaudeville era

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:58.280
and he became a
huge star in that.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:03.110
And by 1920 accordion was a
fairly popular instrument.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.020
And it stayed that
way until about 1930.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:08.000
And the accordion
began to die off

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.590
as it had its kind of
a little bit of a rain.

00:07:11.590 --> 00:07:14.297
And kind of just
stayed in the, it

00:07:14.297 --> 00:07:16.880
wasn't unpopular it just wasn't
really a thing to do, probably

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:21.110
until 1948 when Dick Contino
went on the Horace Heidt

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:23.360
show, which in those days
was kind of like American

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:25.140
Idol on the radio.

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:29.300
And he made the accordion
massively popular at that time.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.310
And that stayed
through the '50s,

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:33.620
until 1962 when
the Beatles landed,

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:37.640
and then that was a
quick, a very quick end

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:39.440
to the accordion.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:42.809
People tell me if you wanted
to be cool in 1960 or so,

00:07:42.809 --> 00:07:43.850
you played the accordion.

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:46.850
And by 1965 you couldn't get a
date if you played accordion.

00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:51.530
So it was an incredible,
really quick drop off.

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:53.940
But during that time,
especially in the '50s,

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:55.970
there were so many
accordion players

00:07:55.970 --> 00:07:58.940
around the United States
and they were just

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:01.430
empires of teaching facilities.

00:08:01.430 --> 00:08:04.520
In Detroit there was
Tony Dannon's empire.

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:08.480
You had Joan Sommers
in Kansas City.

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:11.150
You had the AAA organization
in the east coast.

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:13.670
And there were just thousands
of students playing accordion.

00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:16.130
We produced a lot of world
champions in the '50s

00:08:16.130 --> 00:08:18.030
and into the '60s.

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:20.300
But since the early '60s,
the accordion really died

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:22.430
and by the '80s,
I mean, you didn't

00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:23.730
mention the word accordion.

00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:26.270
It was just absolute no, no.

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:28.040
Weird Al kind of
came out and used it

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:31.970
as a joke a bit in, what,
probably around the '80s.

00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:34.760
But it was still
pretty much a joke.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:39.950
And it died to the point
where it's almost a good thing

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:43.700
because the younger
generation doesn't

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:45.470
know what the
accordion is today,

00:08:45.470 --> 00:08:48.356
because their parents are
the ones that really didn't

00:08:48.356 --> 00:08:49.730
want to talk about
it, especially

00:08:49.730 --> 00:08:50.851
their parents' generation.

00:08:50.851 --> 00:08:52.100
So no one mentioned accordion.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:54.890
So to young people it's
like, what is this thing?

00:08:54.890 --> 00:08:55.921
Yeah, the accordion.

00:08:55.921 --> 00:08:57.420
It doesn't have the
negative stigma.

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.290
I can say just when I was
growing up the negative stigma

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:01.147
was everywhere.

00:09:01.147 --> 00:09:03.230
It was, oh, accordion,
yeah, yeah, the squeezebox,

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:04.160
the polka.

00:09:04.160 --> 00:09:06.487
[POLKA MUSIC]

00:09:06.487 --> 00:09:08.570
And there's a lot of great
polka accordion players

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:10.730
but that was kind of the joke.

00:09:10.730 --> 00:09:13.160
But now I'm seeing it as,
the negative stigma is gone

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:16.362
and it's just becoming this,
what is this instrument?

00:09:16.362 --> 00:09:17.320
So that's where we are.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:19.340
But every country's
history of the accordion

00:09:19.340 --> 00:09:21.720
is completely different.

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:24.060
Brazil, right now,
you play accordion,

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:25.520
that's a very cool thing to do.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:28.680
Argentina, bandoneon,
very cool thing to do.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:31.310
France, playing accordion,
very cool thing to do.

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:35.210
Finland as well,
all of Scandinavia.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:38.005
Russia is very big
on classical music.

00:09:38.005 --> 00:09:39.380
And you'll see
Ljubinka in a bit.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:40.130
She's from Serbia.

00:09:40.130 --> 00:09:42.660
Serbia, playing accordion,
very cool thing to do.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:43.970
It's country by country.

