So it's pretty much,
you're just-- you're always

00:14:16.190 --> 00:14:17.450
thinking in this line.

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:19.820
where am I on the
left hand of the mix?

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:21.960
And then you can mix and match.

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:25.950
So if you play C major
and G major together,

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:28.382
[NOTES] you get a--

00:14:28.382 --> 00:14:29.840
I don't know, for
the theory people

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:31.794
in here-- a C major nine chord.

00:14:31.794 --> 00:14:35.010
[NOTES] So you can
mix and match chords.

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:37.500
But this system
was devised really

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:38.860
to get rid of stride piano.

00:14:38.860 --> 00:14:41.940
If anybody plays stride piano,
it is incredibly difficult

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:44.160
to go doo, doo, doo,
doo, doo, doo, doo.

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:48.090
So instead of doing that, this
is [NOTES] much much, much

00:14:48.090 --> 00:14:49.570
easier is that.

00:14:49.570 --> 00:14:52.260
The problem with this is when I
play jazz and play bass lines,

00:14:52.260 --> 00:14:54.750
I only can use the top two
rows to play bass lines.

00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:57.600
So that gets a little
difficult. And this

00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:59.280
is all within one octave.

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:01.290
So this is why if I keep
going up the scale--

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:02.210
[SCALING NOTES]

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:06.137
--I'll just keep
circling and circling.

00:15:06.137 --> 00:15:07.720
And it's the same
with all the chords.

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:09.712
All the chords are
within one octave.

00:15:09.712 --> 00:15:11.170
But this gives you
at least an idea

00:15:11.170 --> 00:15:13.480
of what is going on
on the left hand.

00:15:13.480 --> 00:15:14.780
Not that complicated, right?

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:15.710
You know, you have
some theories.

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:16.635
It's not that bad.

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:22.560
Now this is the only problem.

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:26.500
What I just showed you is
called the stradella system

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:29.590
on the left hand, which
is one of many systems

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:31.945
that are used in
the accordion world.

00:15:31.945 --> 00:15:33.820
There are many different
kinds of accordions.

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:37.350
So if you have--

00:15:37.350 --> 00:15:39.916
let me just, bellows,
OK, whatever.

00:15:39.916 --> 00:15:41.200
I'm definitely not an artist.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:49.000
If you have a keyboard and
a stradella based system

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.360
like this one, this is
played in the United States,

00:15:52.360 --> 00:15:57.422
in Italy, in Brazil, in
Scotland, half of Russia,

00:15:57.422 --> 00:15:58.130
things like that.

00:15:58.130 --> 00:16:00.250
Now if you get rid
of this and you

00:16:00.250 --> 00:16:02.710
put buttons, which is
what Ljubinka plays,

00:16:02.710 --> 00:16:04.290
which we'll get to
her in a minute.

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:06.460
You have buttons here.

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:11.260
This is played in the other half
of Russia, is played in France,

00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:16.350
is played in Finland and
Sweden and these places.

00:16:16.350 --> 00:16:20.150
But there's many different
systems that this is.

00:16:20.150 --> 00:16:21.900
In Finland, actually,
speaking of Finland,

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:23.230
they have their
own button system.

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:25.896
So they can't really-- they have
to travel with their accordion.

00:16:25.896 --> 00:16:27.684
They can't just go to
Austria and go play

00:16:27.684 --> 00:16:29.350
because it's a totally
different system.

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:31.780
There's a B system, a C
system, different systems.

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:34.420
On the left hand,
there is also free base

00:16:34.420 --> 00:16:37.420
where, remember how I said the
top two rows were single notes?

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:40.510
Well, on a free base, all of
the buttons are single notes.

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:42.160
There are no chords.

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:45.400
That is played pretty
much all of Russia,

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:47.710
it always plays this, the
Eastern European countries

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:48.910
play a lot of this.

00:16:48.910 --> 00:16:50.410
All for classical
music, especially,

00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:52.390
because you can read
piano music directly

00:16:52.390 --> 00:16:54.490
onto the accordion with
a free bass system.

00:16:54.490 --> 00:16:59.410
But then the other thing is,
what if we change the bellows?

00:16:59.410 --> 00:17:02.180
On my instrument when
I play C this way--

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:03.430
let me get rid of the violin--

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:05.540
and I come in, it's
still C, right?

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:07.329
C, C, it doesn't matter.

00:17:07.329 --> 00:17:10.480
On a diatonic accordion,
there's buttons here.

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:14.290
And when I play this button
out, when I come in it's

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:16.119
a different note.

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:17.920
That's a diatonic accordion.

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:22.619
That is what you will see
Mexicans play, or Irish play.

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:24.490
It's funny, Scotland
plays piano accordion.

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:26.322
Irish mostly plays
diatonic accordion.

00:17:26.322 --> 00:17:27.280
Amazing how that works.

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:28.540
Brazil plays this accordion.

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:30.400
Argentina plays the
bandoneon, which is

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:32.080
more like this with the bellow.

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:35.020
So every country is completely
different on which accordion

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:36.670
they play, unlike piano.

00:17:36.670 --> 00:17:39.760
You play piano in Alaska
or you play in Antarctica,

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.130
it's a piano is a
piano, or a trumpet.

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:43.790
This is totally different.

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:46.060
So there's so many different
kinds of accordions.

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:49.240
