00:31:13.662 --> 00:31:15.370
Let's see, what else
here just to go over

00:31:15.370 --> 00:31:17.830
before we get to
different questions,

00:31:17.830 --> 00:31:19.720
because I know
you guys are going

00:31:19.720 --> 00:31:22.303
to have all random questions on
accordion and everything else.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:27.880
But let me do one more
different tune here--

00:31:27.880 --> 00:31:29.540
capabilities of this.

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:31.930
On the percussion sounds on
this particular instrument,

00:31:31.930 --> 00:31:33.721
they are-- a lot of
people think I'm always

00:31:33.721 --> 00:31:35.770
playing with drum
tracks and things

00:31:35.770 --> 00:31:37.900
like this from a computer,
which you actually can.

00:31:37.900 --> 00:31:43.330
I have a USB inside and I can
actually just kind of play

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:45.250
tunes, anything that I want.

00:31:45.250 --> 00:31:48.070
It's like, I've used this
at a party for a boom box.

00:31:48.070 --> 00:31:51.100
My own instrument, which
is kind of interesting.

00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:53.528
You know, you do
something like this.

00:31:53.528 --> 00:31:57.840
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:00.620
Something I recorded before.

00:32:00.620 --> 00:32:02.840
So it's nice because
when I'm traveling

00:32:02.840 --> 00:32:06.860
if the TV needs like a
bump out for something,

00:32:06.860 --> 00:32:09.740
can you just make up some
French thing, or Italian thing,

00:32:09.740 --> 00:32:12.034
or whatever, tango thing,
for no copyrights, you know.

00:32:12.034 --> 00:32:14.450
I can be in my hotel room and
someone can be talking to me

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:17.400
and I can still be recording and
get the USB out and send it off

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:19.490
and we're good to
go, which is really

00:32:19.490 --> 00:32:20.660
cool to have that on board.

00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:23.630
But the drum sounds,
though, they are all

00:32:23.630 --> 00:32:26.062
real of what's going
on over here, even when

00:32:26.062 --> 00:32:27.020
I did the techno thing.

00:32:27.020 --> 00:32:29.610
[DRUM BEATS] So it's
touch sensitive again.

00:32:29.610 --> 00:32:31.810
[DRUM BEATS]

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:32.590
I am playing it.

00:32:32.590 --> 00:32:36.570
If I got rid of everything,
[NOTES] just be an accordion.

00:32:36.570 --> 00:32:37.570
And then the wind, yeah.

00:32:37.570 --> 00:32:40.742
[WIND BLOWING] That
depends if I hold it.

00:32:40.742 --> 00:32:41.700
It has a wind on there.

00:32:41.700 --> 00:32:44.160
There's also thunderstorms,
and you know.

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:46.577
At sound checks, I love
doing the thunderstorm sound

00:32:46.577 --> 00:32:48.660
in a sound check because
then the people freak out

00:32:48.660 --> 00:32:49.870
like what's going on?

00:32:49.870 --> 00:32:54.030
So let's do something
from not too

00:32:54.030 --> 00:32:55.710
long ago that I think
everybody knows.

00:32:55.710 --> 00:32:58.427
This'll be kind of fun
with the drum sounds.

00:32:58.427 --> 00:33:00.415
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:22.449 --> 00:34:27.250
All right, so we can open up
the floor here to questions.

00:34:27.250 --> 00:34:30.760
We want to hand out
the other mic, I think?

00:34:30.760 --> 00:34:32.760
DIVYA PILLAI: Just to get
started, there's one--

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:34.060
CORY PESATURO: Oh,
question over here!

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:35.726
DIVYA PILLAI: There
is one question on--

00:34:35.726 --> 00:34:37.360
so we have a dory.

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:40.780
If you haven't seen it
yet, the GoLink for that is

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:44.139
go/accordion-dory.

00:34:44.139 --> 00:34:47.620
So we have one question
from that, from Denise.

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:49.840
Congrats on breaking the
Guinness World record

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:51.730
in marathon accordion playing.

00:34:51.730 --> 00:34:55.090
How did you train for it?

00:34:55.090 --> 00:34:56.129
CORY PESATURO: Oh boy.

00:34:56.129 --> 00:34:57.670
The answer is, I
didn't train for it.

00:34:57.670 --> 00:35:02.380
I just-- I have a
knack for just kind

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:04.605
of winging a lot of things.

00:35:04.605 --> 00:35:06.130
My most known
world championship,

00:35:06.130 --> 00:35:09.910
which is an acoustic accordion,
I couldn't bring my accordion

00:35:09.910 --> 00:35:10.510
on the plane.

00:35:10.510 --> 00:35:12.218
Like I was saying,
it's always a problem.

00:35:12.218 --> 00:35:14.470
So I just grabbed one there
and they were like, here,

00:35:14.470 --> 00:35:15.340
you just choose accordions.

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:16.600
I was going to wear
an all white outfit

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:17.766
and I saw a white accordion.

00:35:17.766 --> 00:35:19.401
I was like, ah, I
got it, that one.

00:35:19.401 --> 00:35:19.900
It matches.

00:35:19.900 --> 00:35:21.775
It has-- they went,
don't you want to try it?

00:35:21.775 --> 00:35:23.220
Yeah, no, I got to use that one.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:25.540
You know, and I had fun do that.

00:35:25.540 --> 00:35:27.160
But won that.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:29.710
The Guinness record
I said, eh, if I--

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:32.950
I was going to do a
17 hour practice run

00:35:32.950 --> 00:35:35.482
and see how I felt
after 17 hours,

00:35:35.482 --> 00:35:37.690
write down notes and say,
OK, maybe I should do this.

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:40.100
I should have my arm here,
maybe blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:41.560
And I said why even
use the energy?

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:44.380
I'm just going to use all
the energy at the event.

00:35:44.380 --> 00:35:47.060
Just go there and go for it.

00:35:47.060 --> 00:35:50.530
And that's kind of what I
did because it's all mental.

00:35:50.530 --> 00:35:52.750
Your body stops at
hour 10 or 12 and says

00:35:52.750 --> 00:35:54.130
I can't do this anymore.

00:35:54.130 --> 00:35:57.340
My arm was sending all these
awful feelings and signals

00:35:57.340 --> 00:35:58.270
to my hands to stop.

00:35:58.270 --> 00:35:59.609
But my mind was like, nope!

00:35:59.609 --> 00:36:00.400
Have to keep going.

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:01.300
Must keep going.

00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:01.990
It's all mental.

00:36:01.990 --> 00:36:04.160
You've just got to
push through it.

00:36:04.160 --> 00:36:07.870
So, yeah, really the
answer is actually nothing.

00:36:07.870 --> 00:36:09.690
DIVYA PILLAI: Good answer.

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:12.130
Any questions from the audience?

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:13.090
All right.

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:16.262
CORY PESATURO: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:36:16.262 --> 00:36:19.090
Like the end of the race, I
have the official questions.

00:36:19.090 --> 00:36:21.940
AUDIENCE: So what does an
accordion world championship

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:22.740
consist of?

00:36:22.740 --> 00:36:24.190
Like what does that mean?

00:36:24.190 --> 00:36:25.240
How do you win one?

00:36:25.240 --> 00:36:28.089
CORY PESATURO: So they're just
like piano or cello or violin

00:36:28.089 --> 00:36:28.630
competitions.

00:36:28.630 --> 00:36:31.910
There's usually a panel
of about eight judges.

00:36:31.910 --> 00:36:33.880
Some of them have rounds.

00:36:33.880 --> 00:36:36.370
Like the one I was just saying
with the white accordion,

00:36:36.370 --> 00:36:37.900
they had three different rounds.

00:36:37.900 --> 00:36:40.277
And they usually have
national champions

00:36:40.277 --> 00:36:41.860
from different parts
of the world that

00:36:41.860 --> 00:36:45.550
go to one of two main
competitions that

00:36:45.550 --> 00:36:47.530
happen every year.

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:50.650
And actually I'm trying to
get the world championships

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:54.252
to happen in the United States,
either LA or Boston, in 2020.

00:36:54.252 --> 00:36:55.960
Trying to bring that
here because it goes

00:36:55.960 --> 00:36:57.752
to different places every year.

00:36:57.752 --> 00:36:59.460
But it's just like
any other competition.

00:36:59.460 --> 00:37:02.380
They have a big panel of
judges that look very serious

00:37:02.380 --> 00:37:04.090
and you're nervous.

00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:05.560
And there's
different categories.

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:07.930
There's classical
category and then

00:37:07.930 --> 00:37:10.900
there's more of a overall
variety kind of category.

00:37:10.900 --> 00:37:13.022
So just kind of like
any other instrument.

00:37:16.405 --> 00:37:17.780
DIVYA PILLAI: Any
more questions?

00:37:17.780 --> 00:37:18.240
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:18.990
CORY PESATURO: Hi!

00:37:18.990 --> 00:37:20.830
AUDIENCE: Amazing
playing, first of all.

00:37:20.830 --> 00:37:21.210
CORY PESATURO: Thank you.

00:37:21.210 --> 00:37:22.835
AUDIENCE: I am really
impressed by what

00:37:22.835 --> 00:37:26.170
you've been doing and described
and demonstrated today.

00:37:26.170 --> 00:37:28.810
You are pushing the accordion
as a solo instrument.

00:37:28.810 --> 00:37:31.771
Do you also play in
ensembles and if so what

00:37:31.771 --> 00:37:34.270
do you envision as sort of the
future direction of accordion

00:37:34.270 --> 00:37:36.850
as an ensemble instrument
and interactions

00:37:36.850 --> 00:37:38.710
with other accordions
or other instruments?

00:37:38.710 --> 00:37:41.409
CORY PESATURO: Well I mean,
I'm more known as a jazz guy

00:37:41.409 --> 00:37:42.200
than anything else.

00:37:42.200 --> 00:37:45.917
So I, of course, prefer
to play with people.

00:37:45.917 --> 00:37:47.500
And there's always
a kind of a problem

00:37:47.500 --> 00:37:49.420
amongst accordion
players that, because we

00:37:49.420 --> 00:37:54.642
can do so much on our own,
we play alone gigs of lot

00:37:54.642 --> 00:37:56.350
because people can
hire us as like almost

00:37:56.350 --> 00:37:58.030
a trio with the left hand and
everything else, especially

00:37:58.030 --> 00:37:58.960
with this.

00:37:58.960 --> 00:38:02.500
And it becomes a problem
because you know,

00:38:02.500 --> 00:38:05.650
obviously you're a musician,
you don't get good time

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:07.300
when you play alone a lot.

00:38:07.300 --> 00:38:10.970
You need to play with other
people to have a nice set time.

00:38:10.970 --> 00:38:13.960
The other thing is just
musical ideas and collaborating

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:14.919
with different people--

00:38:14.919 --> 00:38:16.335
you know, the
musical interaction,

00:38:16.335 --> 00:38:18.360
especially in jazz or
Eastern European music.

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:19.490
You want to be with people.

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:21.970
So I love playing
with musicians.

00:38:21.970 --> 00:38:25.995
The problem is I get hired
so much as a soloist.

00:38:25.995 --> 00:38:26.620
But it depends.

00:38:26.620 --> 00:38:29.050
What I go to Austria,
that will be a trio.

00:38:29.050 --> 00:38:32.710
At Cotati there'll be a mix
of things, drummer and such

00:38:32.710 --> 00:38:33.320
like that.

00:38:33.320 --> 00:38:36.220
But I mean, the accordion
is currently used,

00:38:36.220 --> 00:38:39.834
certainly all over the world,
in many different ensembles,

00:38:39.834 --> 00:38:42.250
especially in places where
it's still popular like France,

00:38:42.250 --> 00:38:44.474
Argentina, and such.

00:38:44.474 --> 00:38:46.390
But I don't know what
the percentage would be,

00:38:46.390 --> 00:38:51.030
though, of the accordions
used solo or ensemble wise

00:38:51.030 --> 00:38:51.570
currently.

00:38:51.570 --> 00:38:53.030
It's kind of interesting.

00:38:53.030 --> 00:38:54.670
I don't really know.

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:58.052
But any other questions on that?

00:38:58.052 --> 00:39:00.218
AUDIENCE: I can do a follow-up
unless anybody else--

00:39:00.218 --> 00:39:02.552
CORY PESATURO: Yeah, I mean,
you could follow-up, whatever.

00:39:02.552 --> 00:39:03.030
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:39:03.030 --> 00:39:05.155
A follow-up only in the
sense of a second question,

00:39:05.155 --> 00:39:07.630
not actually
related to that one.

00:39:07.630 --> 00:39:09.190
I'm a violinist, by the way.

00:39:09.190 --> 00:39:10.870
I play a lot of
klezmer in Romanian--

00:39:10.870 --> 00:39:11.828
CORY PESATURO: Klezmer!

00:39:11.828 --> 00:39:14.260
Oh, I play more klezmer
gigs than anything,

00:39:14.260 --> 00:39:16.790
actually, because there's
another genre of music where

00:39:16.790 --> 00:39:20.310
the accordion is needed,
as well as violin.

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:23.550
AUDIENCE: And as a
violinist, certainly,

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:27.100
many much of the incredibly
virtuosic Romanian music

00:39:27.100 --> 00:39:30.670
has [INAUDIBLE] over into
the classical violin as well.

00:39:30.670 --> 00:39:32.380
Has that been the
case for accordion?

00:39:32.380 --> 00:39:37.840
Or how has the virtuosity
of those styles of music

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:42.575
influenced other areas
of accordion music?

00:39:42.575 --> 00:39:44.200
CORY PESATURO: The
accordion is kind of

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:50.100
similar to the violin in the
fact that, I think a lot of--

00:39:50.100 --> 00:39:51.760
speaking of Romanian,
in the Balkans

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:53.760
it's like all the best
musicians I've ever heard

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:55.150
seem to be from the Balkans.

00:39:55.150 --> 00:39:56.680
Like you know,
whether it's violin,

00:39:56.680 --> 00:39:58.120
all my favorite
accordion players

00:39:58.120 --> 00:40:02.150
are from, whether it is Serbia,
or Macedonia, or Romania,

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:04.570
Bulgaria especially.

00:40:04.570 --> 00:40:07.360
So it's like the folk
root to the classical root

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:09.060
kind of thing, in how they mix.

00:40:09.060 --> 00:40:11.140
Usually in the
accordion world it's

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:14.822
pretty separated, like it is
I think in the violin world.

00:40:14.822 --> 00:40:16.780
Although some people,
they train as a classical

00:40:16.780 --> 00:40:18.905
until they're 18 or something
and then they kind of

00:40:18.905 --> 00:40:20.200
branch off into something else.

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:23.410
A lot of violinists I play
with went through that.

00:40:23.410 --> 00:40:24.987
I studied a lot
of classical stuff

00:40:24.987 --> 00:40:27.070
because as accordion
players, we don't necessarily

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:29.350
have much classical
accordion music.

00:40:29.350 --> 00:40:32.140
But we do a lot of transcribing.

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:35.110
I played a lot of Tchaikovsky
and things like this

00:40:35.110 --> 00:40:38.950
because it kind of fits
well just on the accordion.

00:40:38.950 --> 00:40:41.075
But usually it is, like
with these competitions,

00:40:41.075 --> 00:40:42.450
the people that
do the classical,

00:40:42.450 --> 00:40:46.040
you don't really see them
doing folk gigs or vice versa.

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:48.070
They're kind of in
separate worlds.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:50.410
But technique
wise, I don't know.

00:40:50.410 --> 00:40:52.990
There is a standard, I'd
say, technique for accordion.

00:40:52.990 --> 00:40:55.690
And actually, speaking of
technique, the right hand

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.630
piano, and the end button
as well, on accordion

00:40:58.630 --> 00:41:01.360
is exactly the same as piano,
the claw kind of thing.

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:04.490
It's really exactly the same.

00:41:04.490 --> 00:41:08.564
It's just, it moves, so you
have to kind of move with it.

00:41:08.564 --> 00:41:11.230
So I haven't done any show where
I've had to dance or something.

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:13.510
That would be-- but
you see violinists.

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:16.400
I mean, they make you guys do
twirls upside down and things.

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:19.310
So it's not that bad.

00:41:19.310 --> 00:41:20.810
And this side is attached.

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:22.210
We have a bass strap here.

00:41:22.210 --> 00:41:23.820
So this doesn't really move.

00:41:23.820 --> 00:41:26.520
But this is kind of a--
this can be a problem.

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:28.440
And it's 25 pounds,
so not the funnest.

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:28.940
But it's OK.

00:41:34.511 --> 00:41:35.636
DIVYA PILLAI: Anymore-- OK.

00:41:39.060 --> 00:41:41.640
AUDIENCE: So you said there
all these types of accordions.

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:43.440
How did you end
up with this one?

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:45.794
Are there any other
types you can play?

00:41:45.794 --> 00:41:46.710
CORY PESATURO: No, no.

00:41:46.710 --> 00:41:48.209
Like I was saying,
the United States

00:41:48.209 --> 00:41:51.470
is like 99% piano accordion.

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:55.560
And in fact, if I think quickly
of the two accordionists

00:41:55.560 --> 00:41:57.630
I know in the US that
play professionally

00:41:57.630 --> 00:42:00.480
that play button accordion,
they came from other countries

00:42:00.480 --> 00:42:02.310
to the United States.

00:42:02.310 --> 00:42:04.970
It's just, it's a very
border to border situation.

00:42:04.970 --> 00:42:11.810
Canada, as well, is pretty much
all piano, when I just learned.

00:42:11.810 --> 00:42:14.520
But as soon as you go to Mexico,
it's all diatonic button--

00:42:14.520 --> 00:42:15.270
totally different.

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:18.390
Portugal, as well,
is kind of the same.

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:19.620
Ireland the same, like that.

00:42:19.620 --> 00:42:21.690
But it's just, yeah,
in the United States

00:42:21.690 --> 00:42:24.060
it's always, always
been piano accordion.

00:42:24.060 --> 00:42:26.760
And no, I can't
really play anything

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:28.640
on any of the other accordions.

00:42:28.640 --> 00:42:30.870
It's totally, totally
a different system.

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:31.770
[DRUM BEAT]

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:34.357
Whoops, sorry.

00:42:34.357 --> 00:42:35.190
Let's turn that off.

00:42:35.190 --> 00:42:39.720
[NOTES] OK, we're back to
accordion, real accordion.

00:42:39.720 --> 00:42:40.870
So no, no, I can't.

00:42:40.870 --> 00:42:43.530
As I said before, I can't even
play "Mary Had a Little Lamb"

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:45.480
on any of the other accordions.

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:47.814
I could kind of learn it, but
the speed I would learn it

00:42:47.814 --> 00:42:49.813
would be the same speed
like you would learn it.

00:42:49.813 --> 00:42:50.610
You know music.

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:52.276
You could kind of
figure out the system.

00:42:52.276 --> 00:42:54.270
But everything else
is totally different.

00:42:54.270 --> 00:42:57.850
The layout of the left
hand, completely different.

00:42:57.850 --> 00:43:00.390
It's not the circle of fifths
and fourths that I showed.

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:02.310
So they're all very different.

