DIVYA PILLAI: I have
a question for you.

00:43:11.470 --> 00:43:12.410
CORY PESATURO: Oh,
you have a question!

00:43:12.410 --> 00:43:13.880
DIVYA PILLAI: Yeah, yeah.

00:43:13.880 --> 00:43:16.830
Because you perform in
so many different styles,

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:19.250
I think you were
trained in, I'm assuming

00:43:19.250 --> 00:43:21.724
New England Conservatory
was more classical?

00:43:21.724 --> 00:43:22.890
CORY PESATURO: No, actually.

00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:23.640
DIVYA PILLAI: No?

00:43:23.640 --> 00:43:25.556
CORY PESATURO: New England
Conservatory really

00:43:25.556 --> 00:43:28.250
opened my ears up
more to more genres

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:31.332
because I played a
fair amount of French.

00:43:31.332 --> 00:43:33.040
Of course I grew up
playing Italian music

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:36.580
and classical music
for competitions.

00:43:36.580 --> 00:43:39.220
That was mainly a kind of
mix of classical and Italian

00:43:39.220 --> 00:43:42.040
and some older pop
kind of things.

00:43:42.040 --> 00:43:47.020
But NEC opened me up to Eastern
European music, odd meters,

00:43:47.020 --> 00:43:48.790
also you know, Brazilian music.

00:43:48.790 --> 00:43:51.090
And I spent a lot of
time learning jazz.

00:43:51.090 --> 00:43:52.962
It takes so long to do that.

00:43:52.962 --> 00:43:54.670
And then all these
other different genres

00:43:54.670 --> 00:43:55.490
around the world.

00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:58.267
So no, because NEC has--

00:43:58.267 --> 00:44:00.100
what's great about New
England Conservatory,

00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:01.830
they have classical,
jazz, like a lot

00:44:01.830 --> 00:44:03.580
of different conservatories,
but they also

00:44:03.580 --> 00:44:05.500
have contemporary improv.

00:44:05.500 --> 00:44:07.720
And the real definition
of contemporary improv

00:44:07.720 --> 00:44:12.550
is, anything that's not
classical and jazz, but also

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:14.770
classical and jazz
kind of messed with.

00:44:14.770 --> 00:44:17.207
So when I went over there,
they were like well,

00:44:17.207 --> 00:44:18.790
we can't put you in
classical or jazz.

00:44:18.790 --> 00:44:21.010
But we can put you
in contemporary,

00:44:21.010 --> 00:44:23.014
which means I could play
classical music-- we

00:44:23.014 --> 00:44:25.430
did a lot of classical music--
and Eastern European music.

00:44:25.430 --> 00:44:29.160
But then, you know, it's a lot
of contemporary stuff like,

00:44:29.160 --> 00:44:31.000
[MUSIC].

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:34.330
Kind of this modern kind
of things and some of that.

00:44:34.330 --> 00:44:37.100
Tapping on the accordion,
different things like this.

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:40.280
And also mixed classical
and jazz, so it was,

00:44:40.280 --> 00:44:44.001
I didn't really do much with
the classical department there.

00:44:44.001 --> 00:44:45.500
So no, that was
really kind of where

00:44:45.500 --> 00:44:50.270
I expanded the genres of what
I could kind of hear and play.

00:44:50.270 --> 00:44:52.250
DIVYA PILLAI: I was
going to ask about,

00:44:52.250 --> 00:44:54.830
I guess some how
you learned improv

00:44:54.830 --> 00:44:57.617
and whether that's
normal, I guess, among--

00:44:57.617 --> 00:44:59.200
CORY PESATURO: How
did I learn improv?

00:44:59.200 --> 00:44:59.991
DIVYA PILLAI: Yeah.

00:44:59.991 --> 00:45:02.950
CORY PESATURO: I've always,
always been an improviser.

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:05.930
Really, I remember a
lesson probably six months

00:45:05.930 --> 00:45:09.597
in where my dad had a record
of Charlie Magnante who

00:45:09.597 --> 00:45:11.830
is one of the other extremely
important accordionists

00:45:11.830 --> 00:45:13.250
in American history.

00:45:13.250 --> 00:45:16.226
And there was just this tune I
liked and I would listen to it.

00:45:16.226 --> 00:45:17.600
I was learning it
by ear and then

00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:18.980
I went in and played
it for my teacher.

00:45:18.980 --> 00:45:20.480
And like, what are you
doing learning music

00:45:20.480 --> 00:45:21.500
without the sheet music?

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:23.480
You know, I was very
much in trouble.

00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:25.760
It really wasn't until
I found jazz I was like,

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:27.340
oh, you're supposed
to improvise!

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:29.420
I like this.

00:45:29.420 --> 00:45:32.630
But I've always been
a huge improviser

00:45:32.630 --> 00:45:36.680
because it makes the
ability to kind of--

00:45:36.680 --> 00:45:39.740
I mean, like what we might
do in a couple of minutes.

00:45:39.740 --> 00:45:42.729
I haven't played that song in I
don't know, probably who knows?

00:45:42.729 --> 00:45:44.270
Trying to remember
the chord changes.

00:45:44.270 --> 00:45:46.604
But it's just an ear thing.

00:45:46.604 --> 00:45:48.020
Obviously like
with your question,

00:45:48.020 --> 00:45:50.060
there's kind of the
different realms

00:45:50.060 --> 00:45:55.160
of teaching where, when you
study for years, especially

00:45:55.160 --> 00:45:57.110
the Russians and
Eastern Europeans,

00:45:57.110 --> 00:45:59.630
that win most of the world
classical championships

00:45:59.630 --> 00:46:01.880
for the past 30 years.

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:03.770
They're practicing six
hours a day or more,

00:46:03.770 --> 00:46:05.390
studying heavy duty
classical music

00:46:05.390 --> 00:46:07.610
but they can't
improvise anything.

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:09.980
And then there's kind of
the other school of thought.

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:13.532
So it's really, I mean, I see it
the exact same in violin world.

00:46:13.532 --> 00:46:14.990
It's the exact same
in piano world.

00:46:14.990 --> 00:46:16.670
It's kind of the same idea.

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:19.930
But I think improvisation
is so important.

00:46:19.930 --> 00:46:23.060
And just, if I hear
something on the radio,

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:24.420
I'm already kind of learning it.

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:27.860
And then I can maybe go
play it at next set gig,

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:30.880
things like this, if I can
decode it quick enough.

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:36.610
Any other questions?

00:46:36.610 --> 00:46:40.350
Or it's La Danza time.

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:40.950
All right.

00:46:40.950 --> 00:46:43.010
Let me get that one ready.

00:46:43.010 --> 00:46:46.500
AUDIENCE: So with the
different types of accordions--

00:46:46.500 --> 00:46:47.870
this is sort of two parts--

00:46:47.870 --> 00:46:52.460
how closely do different
layouts of the accordions

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:55.250
align to the underlying
theory or structures

00:46:55.250 --> 00:46:57.890
of the music in the
different countries?

00:46:57.890 --> 00:47:00.130
CORY PESATURO: That
definitely does.

00:47:00.130 --> 00:47:05.270
AUDIENCE: Like is it easier
to play Finnish music

00:47:05.270 --> 00:47:06.875
on an accordion that--

00:47:06.875 --> 00:47:09.710
CORY PESATURO: Yeah, there
is definitely a bit of that.

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:13.340
Even like the best
example I can think of,

00:47:13.340 --> 00:47:17.010
actually, is, this
is close to home.

00:47:17.010 --> 00:47:20.400
If you listen to like
certain kind of Tejano music

00:47:20.400 --> 00:47:21.990
and different genres
of Mexican music,

00:47:21.990 --> 00:47:24.720
where the accordion is
very important in the band,

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:26.700
there's always an
accordion player,

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:29.760
and they play diatonic
which is the one where

00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:33.480
you hit one note this
way, it's one sound,

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:36.570
and it's a different
one when you come in.

00:47:36.570 --> 00:47:39.630
So it's like when they play,
if they're in the key of G

00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:42.210
and they're playing G, you
know, they're playing this.

00:47:42.210 --> 00:47:44.130
And then when they play D they
have to go out the whole time.

00:47:44.130 --> 00:47:45.390
They have to keep
going out or they

00:47:45.390 --> 00:47:46.514
can't play in the key of D.

00:47:46.514 --> 00:47:50.040
So there's not many keys you
can play in on a diatonic.

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:52.350
When you listen to that
music, usually there's

00:47:52.350 --> 00:47:54.080
not too many ways
and chord changes.

00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:55.552
They kind of stay around home.

00:47:55.552 --> 00:47:56.760
And you can do that on there.

00:47:56.760 --> 00:48:00.150
But there's these licks that
they play, these [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:00.150 --> 00:48:03.660
kind of things, that no matter
how good technique I have,

00:48:03.660 --> 00:48:05.964
I can't do it as clean
and nice as they do it

00:48:05.964 --> 00:48:08.130
because on the diatonic
there's a way they can do it

00:48:08.130 --> 00:48:09.463
with that particular instrument.

00:48:09.463 --> 00:48:10.920
And the same thing
in Irish music.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:13.470
They have these
things to replicate

00:48:13.470 --> 00:48:16.290
what you can do on a violin
with double stops and such.

00:48:16.290 --> 00:48:19.164
And you can do that
easier on a diatonic.

00:48:19.164 --> 00:48:20.330
I can't really do that here.

00:48:20.330 --> 00:48:23.700
It would never sound as clean
or as nice as a diatonic.

00:48:23.700 --> 00:48:25.980
So there is definitely
that aspect to it.

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:29.010
And for classical
music, they mostly

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:31.800
play what Ljubinka
plays because here, I

00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:33.150
don't have a big hand either.

00:48:33.150 --> 00:48:35.810
I can get like a knife nicely.

00:48:35.810 --> 00:48:40.030
This, on a button accordion,
would be two octaves, solidly.

00:48:40.030 --> 00:48:43.150
So you can do a lot more
on the button accordion.

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:46.020
It took the accordion world
to figure out, the piano!

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:47.470
That's not a great system.

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:50.130
It's not symmetrical and
it's too-- this sucks.

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:53.340
And they made a whole new system
that's much more advanced.

00:48:53.340 --> 00:48:56.880
And it's easier to be able to do
these crazy chord, wide chords

00:48:56.880 --> 00:48:58.730
in certain lines and such.

00:48:58.730 --> 00:49:02.104
Also, to change key on a button,
if you're playing a song in C

00:49:02.104 --> 00:49:04.020
and you want to go to
D-flat you just do this.

00:49:04.020 --> 00:49:07.020
You just shift and
it'd be the same.

00:49:07.020 --> 00:49:07.740
So that's better.

00:49:07.740 --> 00:49:09.360
There are other things
that make it much harder

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:11.110
to play that system,
especially because it

00:49:11.110 --> 00:49:13.590
has many more buttons to play
when you're flying around.

00:49:13.590 --> 00:49:15.900
But for classical music,
that system is way better.

00:49:15.900 --> 00:49:18.750
And if you go to the world
championships for classical,

00:49:18.750 --> 00:49:22.445
90% plus play the button
accordion versus this one,

00:49:22.445 --> 00:49:23.820
because it's just
very, very hard

00:49:23.820 --> 00:49:26.220
to be able to do these
crazier things on piano.

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:29.580
It's just not built for it,
mainly because of the distance

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:32.730
that I have here,
even though they

00:49:32.730 --> 00:49:35.170
are smaller than piano
keys as you can tell.

00:49:35.170 --> 00:49:36.520
They're a little bit skinnier.

00:49:39.074 --> 00:49:40.740
AUDIENCE: And then
the sort of continued

00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:42.448
part of that, which
you sort of addressed

00:49:42.448 --> 00:49:46.080
there is, hypothetically if you
could design your own accordion

00:49:46.080 --> 00:49:49.620
completely from scratch without
any engineering constraints

00:49:49.620 --> 00:49:53.400
or anything, like what
would you change or keep

00:49:53.400 --> 00:49:55.200
from this current accordion?

00:49:55.200 --> 00:49:57.840
And especially with going
to like electric accordion,

00:49:57.840 --> 00:49:59.670
are there any
parameters or things

00:49:59.670 --> 00:50:02.010
you wish you could control
more finely that you

00:50:02.010 --> 00:50:03.180
don't have here?

00:50:03.180 --> 00:50:05.940
CORY PESATURO: Well, I mean, the
main problem with accordion--

00:50:05.940 --> 00:50:09.090
look wise, the thing I'm
always trying to change just

00:50:09.090 --> 00:50:10.590
from a marketing
perspective, why

00:50:10.590 --> 00:50:12.530
I've designed this
other accordion that I'm

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:16.860
kind of building with a
different MIT engineer,

00:50:16.860 --> 00:50:18.010
is the look of it.

00:50:18.010 --> 00:50:21.900
You know, when you play
guitar it just looks cool.

00:50:21.900 --> 00:50:23.765
It's light, you can
fly around with it.

00:50:23.765 --> 00:50:25.320
And this, I can't do much with.

00:50:25.320 --> 00:50:26.990
It's just this big--
someone said it

00:50:26.990 --> 00:50:27.880
looks like an air conditioner.

00:50:27.880 --> 00:50:28.500
Yeah, it kind of does.

00:50:28.500 --> 00:50:29.700
It's like this big--
this is why I've done

00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:30.932
all this crazy stuff to it.

00:50:30.932 --> 00:50:32.640
So there's kind of
that marketing aspect.

00:50:32.640 --> 00:50:35.640
I can't be Jimi
Hendrix jumping around

00:50:35.640 --> 00:50:38.267
on stage with this instrument.

00:50:38.267 --> 00:50:40.350
So the weight, yeah, the
weight and the look of it

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:41.500
is one thing.

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:44.610
The other aspect is, technical
wise, playing the bellows,

00:50:44.610 --> 00:50:46.470
you know, it's weird
playing technique here

00:50:46.470 --> 00:50:48.930
when you're moving around.

00:50:48.930 --> 00:50:52.800
So it'd be great if the bellows
were some kind of other system.

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:54.510
Like, if it was,
I thought I needed

00:50:54.510 --> 00:50:56.820
to have just two separate
parts and maybe there

00:50:56.820 --> 00:50:58.590
was a D beam in the middle.

00:50:58.590 --> 00:51:01.650
And something to do
with the distance

00:51:01.650 --> 00:51:03.390
would actually work
as the bellows,

00:51:03.390 --> 00:51:04.870
versus kind of you contained.

00:51:04.870 --> 00:51:08.490
So I had some different designs
of what an accordion could be.

00:51:08.490 --> 00:51:13.530
Almost like two touchpads kind
of thing, something like this.

00:51:13.530 --> 00:51:16.230
Obviously yeah, that system
is kind of a better piano.

00:51:16.230 --> 00:51:17.070
But it depends.

00:51:17.070 --> 00:51:19.295
I love this particular
system with the left hand,

00:51:19.295 --> 00:51:20.670
the stradella
system, because you

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:22.490
can do so many things with it.

00:51:22.490 --> 00:51:24.090
It's good enough
for single notes,

00:51:24.090 --> 00:51:26.730
and the chords you can
do a lot with that.

00:51:26.730 --> 00:51:28.900
So I don't know.

00:51:28.900 --> 00:51:31.890
There's definitely a fair
amount I would change.

00:51:31.890 --> 00:51:34.800
We all look like this
when we're 90%, of course,

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:36.807
because of the weight.

00:51:36.807 --> 00:51:37.890
We all have back problems.

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:39.774
But I don't know.

00:51:39.774 --> 00:51:41.190
And then you throw
it on your back

00:51:41.190 --> 00:51:42.810
and you go this way when you're
walking through the airport.

00:51:42.810 --> 00:51:45.080
So it kind of, in the
end it evens out I guess.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:46.980
It's not too bad.

00:51:46.980 --> 00:51:48.270
How's that?

